<title type="html"><![CDATA[Simple question about modern NES emulators]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5912&amp;p=54854#p54854"><![CDATA[
The GBA can get away with that because the GBA's video hardware is one of the many VDPs <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=5039" class="postlink">heavily inspired by Texas Instruments' TMS9918 VDP</a>, just like the video hardware in NES, Game Boy, PC Engine, and Super NES. Special effects for one translate fairly cleanly to the others. And each of the DS's 2D cores is essentially a GBA PPU.<br /><br />The PC, on the other hand, has more of a Williams model: a dumb frame buffer filled by either a soft blitter or more traditional blitter hardware. The blitter hardware is different enough from the TMS9918 derivatives that the techniques don't translate well.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Fri Jan 08, 2010 1:44 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
